    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="614"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d614">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 365.117/18.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Page</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 52.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 5, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to the Department’s instruction No. 18
                    of the 19th ultimo, I have the honor to state that a careful study and
                    comparison has been made of the language of the proposed circular with the
                    military laws of Italy as at present in force, and that the statements contained
                    in the circular appear to be comprehensive and correct.</p>
                <p>In connection with this general subject I should be glad to know whether the
                    Department would like me to sound the Italian Foreign Office in regard to the
                    possibility of our concluding a naturalization convention with Italy similar to
                    our Convention of 1870 upon the same subject with Austria-Hungary.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thomas Nelson Page</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
